---
/**
 * LautnerBlock — About John Lautner.
 *
 * Editorial block on John Lautner, the LA architect responsible for the
 * Chemosphere, Sheats-Goldstein, Elrod, Garcia, Silvertop, Bob Hope houses.
 * Apprentice of Frank Lloyd Wright, but more Californian, more dramatic,
 * more UFO.
 */
---

<section class="mt-10 mb-8" id="lautner">
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
    <div class="h-px flex-1 bg-rule/40"></div>
    <h2 class="font-mono text-[0.58rem] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-ink-soft/60">
      About &middot; <span class="text-warm">John Lautner</span>
    </h2>
    <div class="h-px flex-1 bg-rule/40"></div>
  </div>

  <article
    class="relative rounded-xl border-2 border-ink/80 bg-card overflow-hidden"
  >
    <!-- Corner blocks -->
    <span class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-3 h-3 bg-warm" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    <span class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-3 h-3 bg-ink" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    <span class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-3 h-3 bg-ink" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    <span class="absolute bottom-0 right-0 w-3 h-3 bg-warm" aria-hidden="true"></span>

    <div class="p-5 md:p-7">
      <p class="font-mono text-[0.52rem] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-warm mb-1">
        1911–1994 · Marquette → Los Angeles
      </p>
      <h3 class="font-heading text-[2rem] md:text-[2.4rem] leading-none text-ink mb-3">
        John Lautner
      </h3>
      <p class="font-serif italic text-[0.95rem] text-ink/80 leading-snug mb-3 max-w-[36rem]">
        Frank Lloyd Wright’s last apprentice who drove west, built a
        version of Los Angeles that never existed anywhere else, and mostly
        got credited as “the Chemosphere guy” for a house he designed on a
        $30,000 budget.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[0.9rem] text-ink/75 leading-relaxed max-w-[36rem] mb-3">
        Chemosphere (1960) sits on a single concrete pole on a 45° slope. The
        Elrod House (1968) has a living room ceiling that looks like a
        concrete octopus rising out of the desert. Goldstein’s Sheats
        (1963) is so iconic the owner bequeathed it to LACMA on purpose.
        Silvertop, Bob Hope, Garcia, Chemosphere — you’ve seen most of
        them in Bond films and Big Lebowski.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[0.9rem] text-ink/75 leading-relaxed max-w-[36rem]">
        His buildings look like the future of the 1960s, which is why the
        future keeps borrowing from them. Every "futuristic house"
        storyboard in Hollywood since 1962 owes him money.
      </p>
      <!-- Per 2026-04-17 direction, blocks don't link off. Houses get
           their own timeline chips instead — tangible facts to scan. -->
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-4">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-sm bg-ink/5 border border-rule/40 font-mono text-[0.5rem] tracking-[0.12em] uppercase text-ink/80">
          <span class="text-warm tabular-nums">1960</span> &middot; Chemosphere
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-sm bg-ink/5 border border-rule/40 font-mono text-[0.5rem] tracking-[0.12em] uppercase text-ink/80">
          <span class="text-warm tabular-nums">1963</span> &middot; Sheats\u2013Goldstein
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-sm bg-ink/5 border border-rule/40 font-mono text-[0.5rem] tracking-[0.12em] uppercase text-ink/80">
          <span class="text-warm tabular-nums">1963</span> &middot; Silvertop
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-sm bg-ink/5 border border-rule/40 font-mono text-[0.5rem] tracking-[0.12em] uppercase text-ink/80">
          <span class="text-warm tabular-nums">1968</span> &middot; Elrod House
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-sm bg-ink/5 border border-rule/40 font-mono text-[0.5rem] tracking-[0.12em] uppercase text-ink/80">
          <span class="text-warm tabular-nums">1973</span> &middot; Bob Hope House
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</section>
